      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":7,\"target_duration_minutes\":43,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":370,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":370,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very relaxed — first 5 minutes are just waking up the legs. Conversational pace throughout.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":33,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable aerobic rhythm. You should be able to hold a full conversation. Heart rate should stay well below threshold.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off the pace for the final 5 minutes. Focus on relaxed breathing and form.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed — the first 5 minutes of easy running IS the warmup. Add a few dynamic leg swings and hip circles before you head out.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 2–3 minutes after finishing, then spend 5–10 minutes on light stretching — calves, hip flexors, and IT band given your history.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your bread-and-butter aerobic run. About 80% of your weekly volume should feel exactly like this — genuinely easy. The physiological goal here is building mitochondrial density and aerobic enzyme activity without accumulating fatigue. If it feels almost too easy, that's exactly right. Easy runs done too fast are one of the most common training mistakes at your level, and they erode the quality of your harder sessions.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Cruise Interval Tempo\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":58,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":370,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":290,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog for 2 km. Use this time to mentally prepare for the work ahead. Finish with 4–5 strides of 20 seconds at tempo effort to prime the system.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":290,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":2,\"notes\":\"2 x 10 minutes at threshold pace (4:50/km). This is comfortably hard — you can speak in short phrases but not hold a conversation. Focus on smooth, controlled turnover.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3-minute easy jog between the two threshold reps. This is active recovery — keep moving, don't stop.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog cooldown. Let your heart rate come down gradually. Resist the urge to stop abruptly.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"2 km easy jog followed by dynamic drills: leg swings, high knees, and 3–4 short strides building to tempo effort. Your body needs a proper on-ramp before threshold work.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"2 km easy jog, then 8–10 minutes of static stretching. Pay particular attention to your IT band and hip flexors — lateral leg swings and a figure-four stretch are your friends here.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Threshold running is the cornerstone of half marathon preparation. Running at your lactate threshold (4:50/km) trains your body to clear lactate more efficiently, which directly raises the pace you can sustain for 21.1 km. The cruise interval format (2 x 10 min with a short recovery) gives you the same stimulus as a continuous 20-minute tempo but with slightly less accumulated stress — a smart progression from your current 4 x 1 km tempo structure. Your target half marathon pace is around 4:59/km, so threshold work at 4:50/km is building the engine you need.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Recovery Easy Run\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":37,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":387,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":387,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":37,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"This run should feel genuinely restorative. Stay at the slower end of your easy range (6:27/km). If your legs feel heavy from Wednesday's tempo, that's normal — keep it easy and trust the process.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"5 minutes of walking and light dynamic movement before you start. No need to rush into running.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 3–5 minutes, then foam roll your IT band, quads, and calves. Given your IT band history, this maintenance work is non-negotiable on a recovery day.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Friday's run serves a specific physiological purpose: it promotes blood flow and active recovery after Thursday's tempo without adding meaningful fatigue. Think of it as flushing the legs rather than building fitness. The temptation to run faster on days like this is real — but running your easy runs too fast is one of the most common ways intermediate runners stall their progress. Slower here means faster on Sunday.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":9,\"target_duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":370,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":271,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2.5 km easy jog. Finish with 4 x 20-second strides at interval effort with full recovery. Your body needs a thorough warmup before VO2max work.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":271,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"4 x 1 km at interval pace (4:31/km). This should feel hard — you're working at roughly 95–98% of max HR by the end of each rep. Controlled aggression. Maintain form even when it gets uncomfortable.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":3,\"notes\":\"3 minutes easy jog between each interval rep. Full recovery is important here — the goal is quality, not accumulated fatigue. If you need an extra 30 seconds, take it.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog to close out. Let your heart rate return to normal gradually.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"2.5 km easy jog is the minimum before interval work. Add dynamic drills and 4 short strides building to interval pace. Your neuromuscular system needs to be fully primed before you ask it to run at 4:31/km.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"2 km easy jog, then thorough stretching session. Saturday is a good day to spend extra time on IT band work — lateral band walks, clamshells, or a foam roll session.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"VO2max intervals are the highest-intensity work in your plan and they serve a critical purpose: raising your aerobic ceiling. By running at 4:31/km — the pace that maximally stresses your oxygen uptake system — you're forcing adaptations that make every pace below it feel more sustainable. For half marathon racing, a higher VO2max means your goal pace of 4:59/km feels more comfortable. Four reps of 1 km is a solid, evidence-based dose for your current fitness level. Note: this is a hard day before your long run, so the long run pace on Sunday must stay genuinely easy. The combination is intentional — it's a classic stress-and-absorb pairing.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Aerobic Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":16,\"target_duration_minutes\":103,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":387,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":387,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":400,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 2 km very easy — almost a shuffle. Let your body wake up before settling into long run rhythm.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":87,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":387,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a steady easy pace (6:27/km). The goal is time on feet, not speed. If you feel good in the final 3 km, you may pick up slightly — but only if the first 13 km felt genuinely comfortable. Stay hydrated and take a gel or some fuel around the 50-minute mark.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":400,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 2 km as a gradual wind-down. Ease off the pace and focus on relaxed breathing.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Dynamic leg swings, hip circles, and a slow 2-minute walk before you start. Long runs don't need a formal warmup — the first 2 km serve that purpose.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 5 minutes immediately after finishing. Then a full 10–15 minute stretching routine: hip flexors, hamstrings, calves, IT band. Consider a light foam roll session later in the day. This recovery investment pays dividends all week.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The long run is the single most important workout in half marathon training. At 16 km this week — a modest step up from your recent 14 km — you're building the aerobic infrastructure that makes 21.1 km feel manageable. The physiological adaptations here include increased glycogen storage, improved fat oxidation, and cardiovascular efficiency. All of these require easy effort to develop properly. Running your long run too fast is the most common mistake in half marathon prep — it turns an aerobic development session into a race simulation, which is fatiguing rather than building. Your long run will build gradually toward 19–20 km over the coming weeks, staying within the 75-minute cap where possible and occasionally extending slightly as race day approaches. Given your IT band history, pay attention to any lateral knee tightness on longer efforts — if you notice anything, flag it early rather than pushing through.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
